    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <head type="title">&#x0201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x0201D; (&#x0201C;Glen of
                    Glenfarg thy beauteous rill&#x0201D;)</head>
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="caps">Title</hi>
                    </head>
                    <p>&#x0201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x0201D; (&#x0201C;Glen of Glenfarg thy
                        beauteous rill&#x0201D;)</p>
                    <p>Ruskin wrote the title as &#x0201C;glen of glenfarg.&#x0201D; He gave
                        the same title to one version of a poem of 1828:
                        &#x0201C;Glenfarg&#x0201D; <hi rend="italic">and</hi>
                        <ref type="works" target="23.html">&#x0201C;Glen of
                            Glenfarg&#x0201D; (&#x0201C;Papa how pretty those icicles
                            are&#x0201D;)</ref>.</p>
                    <p>See <ref type="note" target="titlecitation.html">System of Title Citation for
                            Works</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="caps">Genre</hi>
                    </head>
                    <p>Poem; <ref type="note" target="topographicalpoetry.html">topographical
                            poem</ref>; possible <ref type="note" target="traveldocument.html"
                            >travel document</ref>.</p>
                    <p><ref type="internal" target="#DISCUSSION">See Discussion</ref> for possible
                        connection with travel.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="FACSIMILES">
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="caps">Facsimiles</hi>
                    </head>
                    <p>[none]</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="caps">Major Manuscripts</hi>
                    </head>
                    <p><ref type="mss" target="3.html">MS III</ref> (pp. 66&#x02013;68), a <ref
                            type="note" target="redbook.html">Red Book</ref> devoted primarily to
                            <ref type="works" target="20.html">&#x0201C;Harry and
                            Lucy,&#x0201D; Vol. 2</ref>.</p>
                    <p>In <ref type="mss" target="3.html">MS III</ref>, &#x0201C;Glen of
                        Glenfarg&#x0201D; (&#x0201C;Glen of Glenfarg thy beauteous
                        rill&#x0201D;) is the seventh poem in <ref type="note"
                            target="poetrydiscriptive.html">Poetry Descriptive</ref>. Since this
                        anthology was compiled in 1827, the <ref type="mss" target="3.html">MS
                            III</ref> version may represent a revision or copy of a version, now
                        lost, that was composed in or around September 1826 (<ref type="internal"
                            target="#DATE">see Date</ref>). The existence of a prior version may be
                        indicated by Ruskin&#x02019;s having dropped a rhyme word in the <ref
                            type="mss" target="3.html">MS III</ref> version (see Textual Note).</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="caps">Date</hi>
                    </head>
                    <p>September 1826 (or possibly fall/winter 1827).</p>
                    <p>At the bottom of the first page in <ref type="mss" target="3.html">MS
                            III</ref> containing this poem (it continues onto the next page), <ref
                            type="note" target="ruskinmargaret.html">Margaret Ruskin</ref> wrote
                            &#x0201C;Sep<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> 1826&#x0201D; (in the
                            <ref type="note" target="libraryedition.html">Library Edition</ref>, the
                        hand is incorrectly attributed to <ref type="note"
                            target="ruskinjohnjames.html">John James Ruskin</ref> [<ref
                            type="biblio" target="jrworksle.html">Ruskin, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Works</hi></ref>, 2:257n]). The date appears to refer to this poem
                        in particular, rather than to the entire group of poems to which it belongs,
                            <ref type="note" target="poetrydiscriptive.html">Poetry
                            Descriptive</ref>, a group that dates from a year later, fall/winter
                        1827 (see <ref type="works" target="12.html#DATE"
                            >&#x0201C;Wales&#x0201D;: Date</ref>; and for another case in
                        which Ruskin&#x02019;s parents probably dated a poem separately from the
                        group to which it belongs, see <ref type="works" target="1.html#DATE"
                            >&#x0201C;The Needless Alarm&#x0201D;: Date</ref>).</p>
                    <p><ref type="note" target="collingwoodwg.html">W. G. Collingwood</ref> believed
                        that &#x0201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x0201D; (&#x0201C;Glen of
                        Glenfarg thy beauteous rill&#x0201D;) was inspired by the
                        Ruskins&#x02019; passing through <ref type="note" target="glenfarg.html"
                            >Glen Farg</ref>, in the course of a visit to the family of John
                        James&#x02019;s sister, <ref type="note" target="richardsonjessie.html"
                            >Jessie Richardson</ref>, in <ref type="note" target="perth.html"
                            >Perth</ref>, Scotland. Collingwood assumed they would have started in
                        mid-May, as became usual in later years, and he reasoned, therefore, that
                        Ruskin must have composed this poem dated September 1826 &#x0201C;during
                        the journey home&#x0201D; from this visit (although Collingwood left
                        open the possibility that the family also made an autumn visit, separate
                        from and in addition to the spring journey [<ref type="biblio"
                            target="poems4d1891.html"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> (4<hi
                                rend="superscript">o</hi>, 1891)</ref>, 1:xxiii; <ref type="biblio"
                            target="poems8d1891.html"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> (8<hi
                                rend="superscript">o</hi>, 1891)</ref>, 1:x]). We now know that, in
                        1826, owing to a &#x0201C;barren year&#x0201D; in business, John
                        James was kept away from <ref type="note" target="hernehill.html">Herne
                            Hill</ref> by unusually lengthy business travel until well after his May
                        birthday, and the family holiday was consequently delayed (<ref
                            type="biblio" target="xxx.html"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family
                                Letters</hi></ref>, 1:137, 149, 150 n. 5). Also, any such family
                        journey would have been delayed, and even prevented, owing to the illness
                        and death by consumption of Ruskin&#x02019;s cousin, <ref type="note"
                            target="richardsonjames.html">James Richardson</ref>, which did cause
                        Ruskin&#x02019;s parents to visit Scotland in April of that year, but it
                        is unclear whether Ruskin accompanied them (<ref type="internal"
                            target="#DISCUSSION">see Discussion</ref>; and <ref type="note"
                            target="tours1826-27.html">Tours of 1826&#x02013;27</ref>). Of
                        course, even if Ruskin himself did not travel to Scotland in 1826, nothing
                        prevents his having written in September about <ref type="note"
                            target="glenfarg.html">Glen Farg</ref>. It is also possible, however,
                        that Margaret was simply mistaken in dating the poem September 1826, and
                        that it belongs&#x02014;along with the other poem in <ref type="mss"
                            target="3.html">MS III</ref> on <ref type="note" target="glenfarg.html"
                            >Glen Farg</ref>, <ref type="works" target="23.html">&#x0201C;Glen
                            of Glenfarg&#x0201D; (&#x0201C;Papa how pretty those icicles
                            are&#x0201D;)</ref>, which exists in a firmly dated New
                        Year&#x02019;s 1828 version&#x02014;to fall/winter 1827.</p>
                    <p>See <ref type="note" target="datecitation.html">System of Date
                        Citation</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPPUB">
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="caps">Composition &#38; Publication</hi>
                    </head>
                    <p><ref type="biblio" target="poems4d1891.html"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi>
                                (4<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>, 1891)</ref>,1:xxiv-xxv; <ref
                            type="biblio" target="poems8d1891.html"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi>
                                (8<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>, 1891)</ref>, 1:xi-xii; and <ref
                            type="biblio" target="jrworksle.html">Ruskin, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Works</hi></ref>, 2:257.</p>
                    <p>Hand is ink, print; see <ref type="note" target="ruskinshand.html"
                            >Ruskin&#x02019;s Hand</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DISCUSSION">
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="caps">Discussion</hi>
                    </head>
                    <p>This poem should not definitively be glossed by Ruskin&#x02019;s
                        eyewitness experience of travel to Scotland, as the poem itself forms one of
                        the very few scraps of evidence that he ever took such a journey with his
                        parents prior to 1827; see <ref type="note" target="tours1822-25.html">Tours
                            of 1822&#x02013;25</ref>, and <ref type="note"
                            target="tours1826-27.html">Tours of 1826&#x02013;27</ref>. Of
                        course, it is possible that the poem reliably indicates actual travel, but
                        the tendency of this traditional interpretation to be treated as fact points
                        up the equally important literary and cultural associations with <ref
                            type="note" target="glenfarg.html">Glen Farg</ref>.</p>
                    <p><ref type="note" target="glenfarg.html">Glen Farg</ref> is. . . .</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
